# Artifact Description
The artifact I selected for the databases category is my CS 340 Client/Server Development project, 
originally created during the course as part of an animal shelter dashboard application. This artifact 
used a Python CRUD module connected to a MongoDB database to manage animal records and support 
interactions between the application and the database. I originally created this project during 
CS 340 to demonstrate client-server communication, database connectivity, and structured data management.

# Why I Selected This Artifact
I chose this artifact for my ePortfolio because it highlights important database skills that are valuable 
in computer science and software development. This project shows my ability to work with persistent data, 
organize information in a database environment, and build application logic that retrieves and updates 
records efficiently. I also selected it because it gave me a strong opportunity for enhancement. While the 
original artifact demonstrated basic CRUD functionality, I saw ways to improve its structure, reliability, 
and overall professionalism.

The enhancement improved the artifact by strengthening how the application stores, retrieves, and processes data. 
I improved the CRUD operations by making the code more organized and easier to maintain. I also reviewed how 
requests were sent and managed between the client and the server-side database logic, and I improved the flow 
of validation and error handling. In addition, I made the data-processing logic clearer so the application could 
return results more consistently and in a more usable format. These improvements made the artifact more efficient 
and better aligned with professional database development practices.

This artifact belongs in my ePortfolio because it demonstrates skills in database design, structured data handling, 
debugging, problem solving, and application improvement. It also shows that I can move beyond basic code 
implementation and refine an existing system to make it more functional, reliable, and maintainable.

# Reflection on the Enhancement Process
Through this enhancement, I learned more about the importance of designing software that does not just work, 
but is also well organized and dependable. I gained a better understanding of how database queries, validation, 
and application logic must work together in a client-server environment. This process strengthened my understanding 
of how database systems support larger software solutions and why organization and testing matter when working 
with stored data.

One of the biggest challenges I faced was identifying where the original issues were coming from and deciding 
how to improve the code without disrupting the existing functionality. Another challenge was making sure the 
application managed data correctly and returned meaningful results while keeping the code readable. Working through 
those problems improved both my technical confidence and my understanding of database-centered software design.

I also incorporated feedback by clarifying how the enhancement improved CRUD organization, validation, and database 
reliability within the client-server environment. Revising the narrative in that way made it easier to show exactly 
how the artifact changed and why those improvements matter in a professional setting.

This artifact fully supports Outcome Three and Outcome Four because it demonstrates my ability to design and evaluate 
a computing solution and improve it using appropriate tools and techniques. It also partially supports Outcome Five 
because stronger validation and safer data handling reflect a more security-aware approach, even though security was 
not the primary focus of the enhancement. Outcome Two is also partially supported because the artifact and narrative 
communicate technical work clearly, but the main emphasis of this enhancement is database functionality and improvement.
